    • Enum Constant Detail

      • WFU_COMPOSITE

        public static final JsonUrlOption WFU_COMPOSITE
        The wfu-composite/wfu-implied-composite option. If this option is enabled then application/x-www-form-urlencoded style separators are allowed for an implied top-level object or array.
        See Also:
        JSON→URL specification, section 2.9.3

      • IMPLIED_STRING_LITERALS

        public static final JsonUrlOption IMPLIED_STRING_LITERALS
        The implied-string-literals option. If this option is enabled then all literals are assumed to be strings.
        See Also:
        enableImpliedStringLiterals(Set)

      • EMPTY_UNQUOTED_KEY

        public static final JsonUrlOption EMPTY_UNQUOTED_KEY
        The empty-unquoted-key option. If this option is enabled then the empty string may be represented via a zero length key. Otherwise, two single quotes must be used: ''.

      • EMPTY_UNQUOTED_VALUE

        public static final JsonUrlOption EMPTY_UNQUOTED_VALUE
        The empty-unquoted-value option. If this option is enabled then the empty string may be represented via a zero length value. Otherwise, two single quotes must be used: ''.

      • SKIP_NULLS

        public static final JsonUrlOption SKIP_NULLS
        The skip-nulls option. If this option is enabled then null values in the input or output will be removed.

      • COERCE_NULL_TO_EMPTY_STRING

        public static final JsonUrlOption COERCE_NULL_TO_EMPTY_STRING
        The coerce-null-to-empty-string option. If this option is enabled then null values in the input or output will be replaced with an empty string.

      • AQF

        public static final JsonUrlOption AQF
        Address bar query string friendly.

      • NO_EMPTY_COMPOSITE

        public static final JsonUrlOption NO_EMPTY_COMPOSITE
        Distinguish between an empty object and empty array, and never recognize the empty composite.

        Empty array is back-to-back parens, i.e. (). Empty object is two parens with a single colon inside, i.e. (:). Note that this prevents the parser from recognizing (:) as an object with a single member whose key and value is the unquoted empty string when EMPTY_UNQUOTED_KEY and EMPTY_UNQUOTED_VALUE are also both enabled.

        See Also:
        JSON→URL specification, section 2.9.5

      • enableImpliedStringLiterals

        public static final Set<JsonUrlOption> enableImpliedStringLiterals(Set<JsonUrlOption> set)
        Use this method to enable implied string literals and common related options.

        This is a convenience method for: 

           setOption(Type.EMPTY_UNQUOTED_KEY);
   setOption(Type.EMPTY_UNQUOTED_VALUE);
   setOption(Type.SKIP_NULLS);
   setOption(Type.IMPLIED_STRING_LITERALS);

        If IMPLIED_STRING_LITERALS is true but EMPTY_UNQUOTED_VALUE is false then an attempt to serialize an empty string literal value will trigger an Exception because there wouldn't be any way to represent it.

        If IMPLIED_STRING_LITERALS is true but EMPTY_UNQUOTED_KEY is false then an an attempt to serialize an empty key will trigger an Exception because there wouldn't be any way to represent it.

        If IMPLIED_STRING_LITERALS is true but SKIP_NULLS is false then an an attempt to serialize a null will trigger an Exception because there wouldn't be a way to represent it.

        If you want the above behavior, because your data doesn't support those cases and you want the code to catch them for you, then set the IMPLIED_STRING_LITERALS option directly rather than using this method.

        See Also:
        EMPTY_UNQUOTED_KEY, EMPTY_UNQUOTED_VALUE, SKIP_NULLS, IMPLIED_STRING_LITERALS
